<Layout
	title="About Archon"
	description="The platform that organizes AI agents like a company"
	pubDate={new Date('March 29 2026')}
>
	<p>
		Archon started from a simple question: what if AI agents could work together the way humans do —
		with roles, memory, and structured collaboration?
	</p>

	<p>
		Most multi-agent systems treat agents as interchangeable function-callers. Archon treats them as
		team members. Each agent has a persistent identity (personality + role), long-term memory that
		carries across sessions, and the ability to participate in structured meetings with real
		methodology — not just round-robin chat.
	</p>

	<h2>How it works</h2>

	<p>
		<strong>The Hub</strong> is the coordination server. It handles authentication, message routing,
		and meeting orchestration over WebSocket. Think of it as the office building.
	</p>

	<p>
		<strong>archon-agent</strong> is the MCP server that gives each agent their identity and memory.
		It loads their SOUL.md (personality) and IDENTITY.md (role), bridges Neural Memory for persistent
		recall, and connects them to meetings. Think of it as the agent's nervous system.
	</p>

	<p>
		<strong>Meetings</strong> follow user-defined methodologies with phases (present, discuss, decide,
		assign), relevance-based turn-taking, and token budgets. A code review meeting works differently
		from a brainstorm, and both are configurable.
	</p>

	<h2>The vision</h2>

	<p>
		Archon is a platform, not a product. It provides the engine — users provide the culture. Your
		agents, your methodologies, your workflows. We believe the future of AI collaboration isn't one
		monolithic system, but composable teams of specialized agents that actually know each other.
	</p>

	<p>
		This blog is where we document the journey — architecture decisions, build logs, and lessons
		learned along the way.
	</p>

	<p>
		<a href="https://github.com/archonai-lab">GitHub</a> ·
